{"title_page": "List of Talyllyn Railway rolling stock", "text_new": "{{use British English|date=August 2019}}\n{{short description|List of rolling stock used on the Talyllyn Railway in Wales}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n\n[[File:Talyllyn Cavalcade - 2018-06-16.webm|thumb|right|thumbtime=9|Video showing all steam and diesel locomotives departing Tywyn Wharf]]\nThis is a list of past and present [[rolling stock]] used on the [[Talyllyn Railway]] ({{lang-cy|Rheilffordd Talyllyn}}), a {{RailGauge|2ft3in}} [[narrow gauge railway|narrow gauge]] [[heritage railway|preserved]] [[railway]] line running for {{convert|7.25|mi|km}}<ref name=TRWEB>{{cite web|title=About the Talyllyn Railway|url=http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/about|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|accessdate=5 August 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090809115807/http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/about|archive-date=9 August 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> from [[Tywyn]] on the [[Mid-Wales]] coast to [[Nant Gwernol railway station|Nant Gwernol]] near the village of [[Abergynolwyn]]. The line was opened in 1866 to carry [[slate]] from the quarries at [[Bryn Eglwys]] to Tywyn, and was the first narrow gauge railway in Britain authorised by [[Act of Parliament#United Kingdom|Act of Parliament]] to carry passengers using steam haulage.<ref>{{harvnb|Mitchell|Eyres|2005|p=7}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Boyd|1988|p=44}}</ref> Despite severe under-investment,<ref>{{harvnb|Rolt|1965|p=50}}</ref> the line remained open, and in 1951 it became the first railway in the world to be preserved as a heritage railway by volunteers.<ref>{{harvnb|Thomas|2002|p=32}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Ransom|1996|p=139}}</ref>\n\nWhen first opened, the railway owned two steam locomotives, ''[[Talyllyn (locomotive)|Talyllyn]]'' and ''[[Dolgoch (locomotive)|Dolgoch]]'', and five carriages, including one brake van. There were no additions to the rolling stock until the line was taken over in 1951.{{refn|name=note_a|group=note|There is evidence that during the 1910s, [[Henry Haydn Jones]], the owner of the railway at the time, requested estimates for a new locomotive for the railway.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Newing|first=Don|date=December 2010|title=The Talyllyn Locomotive No. 3 That Never Was|journal=Talyllyn News|issue=228|page=31|issn=0300-3272}}</ref> However, no purchase was made.}} Two ex-[[Corris Railway]] locomotives were then purchased from [[British Rail]]ways, and subsequent additions have brought the total up to six steam locomotives, four diesels and twenty-three carriages.\n\n== Locomotives ==\nThe railway has six steam locomotives for passenger trains and five diesel locomotives that usually haul only works trains. It is unusual for all steam locomotives to be operable at one time, as there is usually at least one locomotive undergoing overhaul.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/node/661 |title=Talyllyn website \u2013 100% availability |publisher=Talyllyn Railway Company |accessdate=5 August 2009 |date=29 August 2007 |author=Higginson, Karen |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221203929/http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/node/661 |archive-date=21 December 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Steam locomotives ===\n{{Hatnote|For technical details about each locomotive, see the relevant locomotive article.}}\n{| class=\"sort wikitable\"\n!Number\n!Name\n!Image\n!width=\"82pt\"|[[Whyte notation]]\n!Builder\n!Works number\n!Date built\n!Current status<br>(as of 19 December 2018)\n!''[[Railway Series]]/[[Thomas & Friends]]'' equivalent<ref name=\"Sodor\">{{cite book|title=Sodor: Reading Between the Lines|last=Awdry|first=Christopher|author-link=Christopher Awdry|publisher=Sodor Enterprises|year=2005|pages=12\u201314|title-link=List of Railway Series books#Sodor: Reading Between the Lines}}</ref>\n{{TR steam locos|\n|number=1\n|name=Talyllyn\n|image=Tal-y-Llyn (19435419666).jpg\n|alt=Talyllyn at Tywyn Wharf\n|whyte={{Whyte|0-4-2|ST}}<ref name=No1>{{cite web|title=No. 1 'Talyllyn'|url=https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-1-talyllyn|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|accessdate=20 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181220230637/https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-1-talyllyn|archive-date=20 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|builder=[[Fletcher, Jennings & Co.|Fletcher,&nbsp;Jennings<br />&&nbsp;Co.]], Whitehaven<ref name=No1/>\n|worksno=42<ref name=No1/>\n|built=1864<ref name=No1/>\n|status= Undergoing overhaul.<ref name=No1/>\n|rseries=[[Skarloey]]\n[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Minor Characters|''Rusty's Ghost Engine'']] <small>''(Thomas & Friends only)</small>\n|notes=One of two original locomotives, it was built as an {{whyte|0-4-0|ST}} without a cab. By 1866, trailing wheels had been added to improve stability, and it had a cab installed at the same time.<ref name=No1/> It was named after the railway.}}\n\n{{TR steam locos\n|number=2\n|name=Dolgoch\n|image=Dolgoch (18838965524).jpg\n|alt=Dolgoch at Tywyn Wharf\n|whyte={{Whyte|0-4-0|WT}}<ref name=No2>{{cite web|title=No. 2 'Dolgoch'|url=https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-2-dolgoch|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|accessdate=20 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024073736/https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-2-dolgoch|archive-date=24 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|builder=Fletcher,&nbsp;Jennings<br />&&nbsp;Co., Whitehaven<ref name=No2/>\n|worksno=63<ref name=No2/>\n|built=1866<ref name=No2/>\n|status=In service<ref name=No2/>\n|rseries=[[Rheneas]]\n[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Minor Characters|''Smudger'']] <small>''(Thomas & Friends only)</small>\n|notes=The second original locomotive. Like ''Talyllyn'', it was built without a cab, though one was subsequently added. It was named after the intermediate station and local waterfalls, though after the [[Second Boer War|Boer War]], it carried the name ''[[Pretoria]]'' for several years. In 2011 it received a new boiler, and returned to steam in time for the 60th anniversary celebrations of the preservation society on 14 May.}}\n\n{{TR steam locos\n|number=3\n|name=Sir Haydn\n|image=Talyllyn Railway No. 3 Sir Haydn - 2018-06-16.jpg\n|alt=Sir Haydn at Abergynolywn\n|whyte={{Whyte|0-4-2|ST}}<ref name=No3>{{cite web|title=No. 3 'Sir Haydn'|url=https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-3-sir-haydn|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|accessdate=20 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701082555/https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-3-sir-haydn|archive-date=1 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|builder=Hughes,<br /> [[Falcon Works]],<br /> [[Loughborough]]<ref name=No3/>\n|worksno=323<ref name=No3/>\n|built=1878<ref name=No3/>\n|status=In service<ref name=No3/>\n|rseries=[[Sir Handel]]\n[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Minor Characters|''Proteus'']] <small>''(Thomas & Friends only)</small>\n\n[[Mid Sodor Railway#Locomotives|''Albert'']] <small>''(Railway Series only)</small>\n|notes=An ex-[[Corris Railway]] locomotive, purchased in 1951 and subsequently named after [[Henry Haydn Jones|Sir Henry Haydn Jones]], owner of the railway prior to preservation. Following the expiry of its 10-year boiler ticket in early 2012, the loco was stored out of use at the Corris Railway until April 2013, when it commenced a tour of various railway sites in England to help raise funds for its overhaul. In February 2015 it was moved back to the Talyllyn. In Autumn 2015 it was sent to the [[Vale of Rheidol Railway]]'s new workshop in [[Aberystwyth]] for its overhaul to start. It returned to service in 2018, in time for its 140th birthday.}}\n\n{{TR steam locos\n|number=4\n|name=Edward Thomas\n|image=Edward Thomas (13796797195).jpg\n|alt=Edward Thomas at Tywyn Wharf\n|whyte={{Whyte|0-4-2|ST}}<ref name=No4>{{cite web|title=No. 4 'Edward Thomas'|url=https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-4-edward-thomas|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|accessdate=20 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181220230933/https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-4-edward-thomas|archive-date=20 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|builder=[[Kerr Stuart]],<br>[[Stoke-on-Trent]]<ref name=No4/>\n|worksno=4047<ref name=No4/>\n|built=1921<ref name=No4/>\n|status=In service<ref name=No4/>\n|rseries=[[Peter Sam]]\n|notes=The second ex-Corris Railway locomotive, also purchased in 1951 and subsequently named after the general manager of the line prior to preservation. It was fitted with a [[Giesl ejector]] between 1958 and 1969.<ref>{{harvnb|Potter|1990|p=198}}</ref> Received a new boiler in 2004.}}\n\n{{TR steam locos\n|number=6\n|name=Douglas\n|image=No. 6 Douglas in RAF blue - 2018-02-21.jpg\n|alt=Douglas at Tywyn Wharf\n|whyte={{Whyte|0-4-0|WT}}<ref name=No6>{{cite web|title=No. 6 'Douglas'/'Duncan'|url=https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-6-douglas-duncan|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|accessdate=20 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701082614/https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-6-douglas-duncan|archive-date=1 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|builder=[[Andrew Barclay Sons & Co.|Andrew Barclay]], [[Kilmarnock]]<ref name=No6/>\n|worksno=1431<ref name=No6/>\n|built=1918<ref name=No6/>\n|status=In service<ref name=No6/>\n|rseries=[[Duncan (fictional locomotive)|Duncan]]\n|notes=A \"Modified E Class\", built for the depot railway serving [[RAF Calshot]].<ref>{{harvnb|Boyd|1970|pp=100\u2013101}}</ref> It was donated to the Talyllyn in 1953, regauged from {{RailGauge|2ft}} gauge and named after Douglas Abelson, who donated the locomotive.<ref>{{harvnb|Morland|2005|p=21}}</ref>\nReturned to service July 2013 as 'Douglas' in bright red and black border livery. Repainted to RAF blue livery in March 2018.}}\n\n{{TR steam locos\n|number=7\n|name=Tom Rolt\n|image=Tom Rolt (14726150433).jpg\n|alt=Tom Rolt at Tywyn Wharf\n|whyte={{Whyte|0-4-2|T}}<ref name=No7>{{cite web|title=No. 7 'Tom Rolt'|url=https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-7-tom-rolt|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|accessdate=20 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181220230941/https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-7-tom-rolt|archive-date=20 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|builder=Talyllyn Railway<ref name=No7/>\n|worksno=none given<ref name=No7/>\n|built=1991<ref name=No7/>{{refn|name=TomRolt|group=note|This refers to the year the locomotive was built by the Talyllyn. The Bord na M\u00f3na locomotive used for some of the constituent parts was built in 1949.}}\n|status=In service<ref name=No7/>\n|rseries=[[Skarloey Railway#Locomotives|Ivo Hugh]] <small>(Railway Series Only)</small>\n|notes=This locomotive was built by the Talyllyn Railway using components from a [[Bord na M\u00f3na]] (Irish Peat Board) Andrew Barclay locomotive. It was originally intended to give it the jocular name ''Irish Pete''. However, prior to completion, it was decided to name it in honour of [[L.T.C. Rolt]], one of the founders of the Talyllyn Railway Preservation Society.}} Returned to service in 2019 following a ten-yearly overhaul.\n|}\n\n=== Diesel locomotives ===\n{| class=\"sort wikitable\"\n!Number\n!Name\n!Image\n!Type\n!Builder\n!Date built\n!Power ([[Horsepower|hp]])<ref name=Bate257>{{harvnb|Bate|2001|p=257}}</ref>\n!Wheel diameter<ref name=Bate257/>\n!''Railway Series/Thomas & Friends'' equivalent<ref name=\"Sodor\"/>\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|5\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''Midlander''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Railway Midlander No 5.jpg|150px|Midlander at Pendre]]\n|align=\"center\" | {{whyte|4w|DM}}\n|[[Ruston & Hornsby]]\n|1941<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/news/outing-no-5s-70th-birthday|title=An Outing for No. 5's 70th Birthday|date=9 February 2010|accessdate=21 September 2012|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401132720/http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/news/outing-no-5s-70th-birthday|archive-date=1 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|48\n|{{convert|1|ft|6|in|abbr=on}}\n|''[[Rusty (locomotive)|Rusty]]''\n|-\n|colspan=6|This locomotive was purchased in 1957 from Jee's quarries at [[Hartshill]],<ref>{{harvnb|Potter|1990|p=201}}</ref> and contains parts that were cannibalised off an identical locomotive. It was named after the [[English Midlands|Midlands]] area group of the preservation society that donated the locomotive.\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|9\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''Alf''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Railway No 9 Alf - 2008-03-18.jpg|150px|Alf at Pendre]]\n|align=\"center\" | {{whyte|0-4-0|DM}}\n|[[Hunslet Engine Co.]]\n|1950\n|75\n|{{convert|2|ft|abbr=on}}\n|''[[Fred (locomotive)|Fred]]'' <small>(Railway Series Only)</small>\n|-\n|colspan=6|This is an ex-[[National Coal Board]] locomotive, from [[Huncoat]] colliery in [[Lancashire]].<ref name=Potter202/> It was named after [[Alfred Robens, Baron Robens of Woldingham|Alf Robens]], chairman of the National Coal Board.<ref>{{harvnb|Morland|2005|p=13}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|11\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''Trecwn''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Railway No 11 Trecwn - 2018-06-16.jpg|150px|Trecwn at Nant Gwernol]]\n|align=\"center\" | {{whyte|4w|DH}}\n|[[Ernest E. Baguley|Baguley]]\n|1983-84<ref name=\"IRS 15EL\" />\n|99\n|610mm\n|\n|-\n|colspan=6|One of three Baguley diesels that were purchased from [[RNAD Trecwn]] in South Wales in 2008. These were originally bought by a consortium of volunteers, but have since been purchased from this group by the railway. This loco was originally numbered T&nbsp;0006&nbsp;00&nbsp;NZ&nbsp;32 (BD&nbsp;3764)<ref name=\"IRS 15EL\" /><ref name=otherlocos>{{Cite web|url=https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/enthusiasts/locomotives|title=Locomotives|accessdate=11 October 2019|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328155509/https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/enthusiasts/locomotives|archive-date=28 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and entered service on the Talyllyn in 2014.\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|12\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''St. Cadfan''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:No. 12 St. Cadfan - 2018-02-21.jpg|150px|St. Cadfan at Wharf]]\n|align=\"center\" | {{whyte|4w|DH}}\n|Baguley\n|1983-84<ref name=\"IRS 15EL\" />\n|99\n|610mm\n|\n|-\n|colspan=6|The second of the three Baguley diesels that were purchased from [[RNAD Trecwn]] in South Wales in 2008.{{refn|name=note_d|group=note|The third loco, formerly T 0009 00 NZ 35 (BD 3781), will not operate on the railway, but is being used for spares.}} This loco was originally numbered BD 3779<ref name=\"IRS 15EL\" /><ref name=\"otherlocos\"/> and named after [[St Cadfan's Church, Tywyn|St Cadfan's Church]] in Tywyn.\n|}\n\n=== Self-propelled engineering plant ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Name\n!Image\n!Type\n!Builder\n!Date built\n|- style=\"height:113px\"\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''Toby''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Motor Trolley \"Toby\" on Talyllyn Railway - 2008-03-18.jpg|100px|Permanent Way Trolley]]\n|Permanent Way Trolley\n|John Bate<ref name=Toby>{{Cite web|url=https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/news/toby-returns|title='Toby' Returns!|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|accessdate=19 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619212546/https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/news/toby-returns|archive-date=19 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|1954<ref name=Toby/>\n|-\n|colspan=3|Small trolley used by engineers for transportation to worksites. Built from a second hand [[Austin 7]] engine and gearbox, mounted on a custom-made chassis.<ref>{{harvnb|Bate|2001|p=42}}</ref> It was damaged in a shunting accident in 2008 and taken out of service, but returned to use in 2019.<ref name=Toby/>\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"| -\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Tamper.JPG|150px|Matisa ballast tamper]]\n|[[Ballast tamper]]\n|Matisa<ref name=Matisa>{{cite web|url=http://www.matisa.ch/|title=Manufacturer's website|access-date=13 March 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080321003522/http://www.matisa.ch/|archive-date=21 March 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|1990\n|-\n|colspan=3|Rail mounted track tamper. Parts of two ex-[[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|MOD]] [[standard gauge]] tampers were acquired in 1989 and one complete machine was assembled and commissioned on 26 June 1990.<ref>{{harvnb|Bate|2001|pp=230\u2013231}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"| -\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Flail mover.JPG|150px|Flail mower]]\n|Flail Mower\n|Talyllyn Railway\n|1998\n|-\n|colspan=3|Rail mounted self-propelled vehicle used to clear lineside vegetation.<ref>{{harvnb|Morland|2005|p=40}}</ref> Designed by John Bate (Chief Engineer 1963-1994) and built from chassis components from two [[Ruston (engine builder)|Ruston & Hornsby]] locomotives, the framing and motor components of a [[Smalley (excavator)|Smalley]] excavator, the flail mechanism and cab from a McConnel [[flail mower]] and a new [[Perkins Engines|Perkins]] diesel power unit.<ref>{{harvnb|Bate|2001|pp=248\u2013249}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Former locomotives===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Number\n!Name\n!Image\n!Type\n!Builder\n!Date built\n!Power ([[Horsepower|hp]])\n!Year with-<br />drawn\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|5\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''\"The Lawnmower\"''<ref name=Bate33>{{harvnb|Bate|2001|p=33}}</ref><ref group=note>Names in inverted commas refer to unofficial nick-names, not formally applied.</ref>\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|\n|align=\"center\" | {{whyte|4w|PH}}\n|[[David Curwen]]\n|1952\n|20<ref>{{harvnb|Boyd|1970|p=98}}</ref>\n|1953\n|-\n|colspan=5|This lightweight locomotive was built by member David Curwen using a [[Ford Model T]] engine and transmission from L.T.C Rolt's [[narrowboat]] and the wheels from a Talyllyn Railway [[slate wagon]]. It worked the Fridays-only winter passenger service until 1953,<ref name=RMJan2013>{{cite magazine|date=January 2013|title=Historic Talyllyn loco to be resurrected|magazine=[[The Railway Magazine]]|page=93}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Boyd|1970|p=99}}</ref> when it was taken out of use with a failed gearbox. It was dismantled in 1954,<ref name=Bate33/> and converted to flat wagon No. 19 (see below).<ref name=stocklist/> It is proposed to rebuild it as a memorial to David Curwen, using a replacement engine and bodywork.<ref name=RMJan2013/>\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|7\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''\"Charley's Ant\"''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|\n|align=\"center\" | 4-2-0\n|Talyllyn Railway\n|1954\n|\n|c.1958\n|-\n|colspan=5|A Mercury [[tractor]] that had been adapted to push standard gauge rolling stock by the addition of a [[buffer beam]]. It was further adapted in 1954 for use on the Talyllyn, and later converted to run on paraffin instead of petrol.<ref>{{harvnb|Boyd|1970|p=102}}</ref> It was little used after 1958 and later scrapped. It was nicknamed after Charles Uren, the railway's chief engineer.<ref name=Potter202/>\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|8\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''Merseysider''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Merseysider at Nant Gwernol - 2006-03-05.jpg|150px|Merseysider at Nant Gwernol]]\n|align=\"center\" | {{whyte|4w|DH}}\n|Ruston & Hornsby\n|1964\n|50\n|2016\n|-\n|colspan=6|This was originally built using parts from three {{RailGauge|3ft}} gauge locomotives from Park Gate [[steelworks]] in [[Rotherham]], acquired in 1969.<ref name=Potter202>{{harvnb|Potter|1990|p=202}}</ref> The superstructure was replaced c. 2000. It has a Dowty [[Transmission (mechanics)#Hydrostatic|hydrostatic transmission]]. The name was chosen by the donor of the locomotive.<ref>{{harvnb|Morland|2005|p=41}}</ref> This locomotive was sold in 2016. \n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|10\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''Bryn Eglwys''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Railway No 10 Bryn Eglwys - 2009-03-01.jpg|150px|Bryn Eglwys at Wharf]]\n|align=\"center\" | {{whyte|4w|DH}}\n|[[Motor Rail]]\n|1985\n|110\n|2014\n|-\n|colspan=5|This was originally a {{RailGauge|2ft6in}} gauge National Coal Board locomotive from Hem Heath colliery near [[Stoke-on-Trent]].<ref>{{cite book|chapter=Engineering Report |title=Talyllyn News|edition= issue 175 (September 1997) |page=6}}</ref> It arrived on the Talyllyn September 1997,<ref name=otherlocos/> and was re-painted into standard Talyllyn livery during summer 2005. The locomotive was named after the [[Bryn Eglwys]] slate quarries. The loco was sold to the [[North Gloucestershire Railway]],<ref name=CouncilRep13>{{Cite web|url=http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/internal/arrc-14c|title=Report of the Council for 2013|accessdate=22 September 2014|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924043712/http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/internal/arrc-14c|archive-date=24 September 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> and left the railway in August 2014 when the first Baguley loco entered service.\n|}\n\n=== Visiting locomotives ===\n{{As of|2015}} there have only been two visiting locomotives capable of running on the Talyllyn Railway's unusual gauge. These are [[Motor Rail]] Simplex diesel No. 5 ''Alan Meaden'' and [[Winson Engineering]] and Drayton Designs No. 7 ''Tattoo'' class design<ref name=TRCORRISNEWS>{{cite web|title=Announcing the Corris Weekend & CR 7 Visit|url=http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/news/corris-railway-no-7-visit|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|date=6 October 2011|accessdate=6 October 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111023002213/http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/news/corris-railway-no-7-visit|archive-date=23 October 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> similar to the Talyllyn's No. 4. Both these are locomotives from the Corris Railway.\n\nIn July 2015 a gala was held to mark the railway's 150th anniversary, and two {{railgauge|23.5in}} gauge locomotives visited the railway: [[George England and Co.]] locomotive ''[[Festiniog Railway 0-4-0TT|Prince]]'' from the [[Ffestiniog Railway]] and [[Hunslet Engine Company]] ''[[Russell (locomotive)|Russell]]'' from the [[Welsh Highland Heritage Railway]], both in [[Porthmadog]]. Two lengths of temporary track were laid at {{stnlnk|Tywyn Wharf}} to allow the locomotives to operate over a short distance.\n\nIn July 2016, another gala was held, with three visiting locos, all built by Fletcher, Jennings and Co. Together with ''Talyllyn'' and ''Dolgoch'', this was an assembly of all five surviving locos in the UK built by this firm.<ref>{{Cite news|title=150th anniversary of Dolgoch finale|publisher=Cambrian News|date=11 July 2016|url=http://www.cambrian-news.co.uk/article.cfm?id=106273&headline=150th+anniversary+of+Dolgoch+finale&sectionIs=news&searchyear=2016|accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref> As with the previous gala, temporary track was laid due to the differing gauges.<ref name=SR2016>{{Cite web|title=Five engines, three gauges, one railway|url=https://www.steamrailway.co.uk/steamnews/2016/7/15/five-engines-three-gauges-one-railway|publisher=Steam Railway|date=15 July 2016|accessdate=5 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007230417/http://www.steamrailway.co.uk/steamnews/2016/7/15/five-engines-three-gauges-one-railway|archive-date=7 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> One of the locomotives, ''[[Rolling stock of the Bluebell Railway|Captain Baxter]]'', ran on a short section of [[standard gauge]] track. The other two Fletcher Jennings locomotives, ''William Finlay'' and ''[[Townsend Hook]]'' were static exhibits only, and are therefore not listed below. ''William Finlay'' remained at Tywyn after the event and is now on display at the [[Narrow Gauge Railway Museum]].\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Number\n!Name\n!Image\n!&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Type&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n!Builder\n!Date built\n!''[[Railway Series]]/[[Thomas & Friends]]'' equivalent<ref name=\"Sodor\" />\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|5\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''Alan Meaden''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Corris No 5 - 2012-05-07.jpg|150px|Alan Meaden on the Corris Railway]]\n|{{whyte|4w|DM}}\n|[[Motor Rail]] Simplex\n|1965\n|-\n|colspan=3|A former {{RailGauge|2ft}} gauge diesel from Staveley Lime Products, Hindlow, Derbyshire, named in honour of the Corris Society's founder. It visited the Talyllyn in 1983 and 1990.<ref>{{harvnb|Bate|2001|p=205}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|7\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|(unnamed)\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Corris loco 7 on Talyllyn - 2011-10-23 (cropped).jpg|150px|Corris No. 7]]\n|{{Whyte|0-4-2|ST}}\n|[[Winson Engineering]] and Drayton Designs\n|2005\n|-\n|colspan=3|Built for the Corris Railway, based on the Kerr Stuart \"Tattoo\" class design of Corris No. 4. It visited the Talyllyn in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Corris No 7 Visit - 7th and 8th October 2011|url=http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/news/corris-no-7-visit-7th-and-8th-october-2011|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|date=8 October 2011|accessdate=8 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111023002208/http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/news/corris-no-7-visit-7th-and-8th-october-2011|archive-date=23 October 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|2\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''Prince''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Prince at Tywyn Wharf - 2015-07-04.jpg|150px|Prince]]\n|{{Whyte|0-4-0|TT}}{{refn|name=note_tt|group=note|TT denotes a [[tank locomotive]] with additional [[Tender (rail)|tender]].}}\n|George England and Co.\n|1864<ref name=FFR>{{Quine-FR}}</ref>{{refn|name=note_fr|group=note|Some sources state that ''Prince'' was built in 1863.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ffestiniograilway.org.uk/full_article?a=ffestiniog-locomotives|title=Ffestiniog locomotives|publisher=Ffestiniog Railway Society|date=1 January 2014|accessdate=9 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924012045/http://www.ffestiniograilway.org.uk/full_article?a=ffestiniog-locomotives|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live|series=[[Mid Sodor Railway#Locomotives|Duke]] [[Bertram]] <small>(Thomas & Friends only]] </small>}}</ref>}}\n|colspan=3|''Prince'' was built in 1863 for the [[Ffestiniog Railway]] and is the oldest FR locomotive still in operating condition. It has spent all of its working life on the FR, but in 2015 ran on a short length of {{RailGauge|1ft11.5in}} gauge track laid at Tywyn Wharf station as part of the TR's 150th. anniversary celebrations.\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|(unnumbered)\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''Russell''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Russell (19435415896).jpg|150px|Russell]]\n|{{Whyte|2-6-2|T}}\n|Hunslet Engine Co.\n|1906\n|rseries=[[Skarloey Railway#Locomotives|''Duke'']]\n|-\n|colspan=3|Built in 1906 for the [[North Wales Narrow Gauge Railways|NWNGR]], ''Russell'' later ran on the [[Welsh Highland Railway]]. After the WHR closed in 1937 it moved to the [[Brymbo Ironworks railway]] and then in 1946 to [[Purbeck Ball Clay|Fayle's Tramway]] in Dorset. It was rescued for preservation in 1954 and between 1955, and 1965 ''Russell'' was on display as a static exhibit outside the [[Narrow Gauge Railway Museum]] at Tywyn. Since 1965 the locomotive has belonged the [[Welsh Highland Heritage Railway|WHHR]]. It visited Tywyn again in 2015 as part of the TR's 150th. anniversary celebrations.\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|3\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''Captain Baxter''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Captain Baxter at Tywyn Wharf - 2016-07-02.jpg|150px|Captain Baxter]]\n|{{Whyte|0-4-0|T}}\n|Fletcher, Jennings and Co.\n|1877\n|-\n|colspan=3|A standard gauge locomotive, built in 1877 for the [[Betchworth railway station#Betchworth Quarry Railways|Betchworth Quarry Railways]] in Surrey. It is preserved by the [[Bluebell Railway]] in West Sussex.\n|}\n\n==Carriages==\nThe Talyllyn railway has a total of 23 [[Passenger car (rail)|carriages]]. The first five are the original carriages built for the railway, though they were not provided with numbers until preservation in 1951. After that time, the remaining carriages were built by the railway or acquired from elsewhere.<ref name=summary>{{Cite web|url=http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/details/summary|title=Talyllyn Railway Carriage Summary|accessdate=5 August 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100312044754/http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/details/summary|archive-date=12 March 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> With the exception of ex-Corris carriage No. 17, all the [[bogie]] coaches were built for the railway after preservation; the smaller four wheeled coaches are generally older.\n\nAll the stock is third class only, unless otherwise stated. Where two figures are given for the number of seats, the larger figure is the maximum number of passengers than can be carried in a heavily loaded train.\n\n===Four wheeled carriages===\n{| class=\"sort wikitable sortable\"\n!Number\n!Image\n!Builder\n!Date built\n!Seats<ref name=summary/>\n!Notes\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3746|title=Carriage 1 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=24 August 2003|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Carriage 1.JPG|150px|Carriage No. 1]]\n|[[Brown, Marshalls and Co. Ltd.|Brown, Marshalls]]\n|1866\n|18\n|This was originally a first class carriage; it is now third class.<ref name=Boyd282>{{harvnb|Boyd|1988|p=282}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3747|title=Carriage 2 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=28 June 2000|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Carriage No 2.JPG|150px|Carriage No. 2]]\n|[[Brown, Marshalls and Co. Ltd.|Brown, Marshalls]]\n|1866\n|18\n|\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|3<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3748|title=Carriage 3 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=24 August 2003|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Carriage 3.JPG|150px|Carriage No. 3]]\n|[[Brown, Marshalls and Co. Ltd.|Brown, Marshalls]]\n|1866\n|18\n|This was the first carriage to be delivered,<ref>{{harvnb|Boyd|1988|p=46}}</ref> and is {{convert|1|foot|cm}} shorter than Nos. 1 and 2. Originally third class, it was later changed to composite (first and third class), but is now third class again.<ref name=Boyd282/>\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|4<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3749|title=Carriage 4 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=28 June 2000|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:LimpingLulu1898.jpg|150px|Carriage No. 4]]\n|[[Lancaster Carriage and Wagon Works]]\n|1867\n|18\n|In the 1950s, this carriage was known as \"''Limping Lulu''\" to railway staff due to the poor state of the frames, which were replaced in 1958.<ref>{{harvnb|Potter|1990|p=204}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|5<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3750|title=Carriage 5 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=28 June 2000|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Rly Guards Van No.5 Abergynolwyn May 2015.jpg|150px|Brake van No. 5]]\n|[[Brown, Marshalls and Co. Ltd.|Brown, Marshalls]]\n|1866\n|none\n|This was the original [[brake van|guard's van]]. It was out of use between 1946 and April 1949 while its wheels were repaired at the Britannia Foundry in Porthmadog.<ref>{{cite journal |journal=Talyllyn News |date=March 2015 |title=The Talyllyn Railway in the late Haydn Jones era |author=Dan Quine}}</ref>\n|- style=\"height:113px\"\n|align=\"center\"|6<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3769|title=Carriage 6 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=28 June 2000|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Corris van 6 - 2011-10-23.jpg|150px|Brake van No. 6]]\n|[[Falcon Works]]\n|1885\n|none\n|This guard's van was originally from the [[Corris Railway]].\n|- style=\"height:113px\"\n|align=\"center\"|7<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3771|title=Carriage 7 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=28 June 2000|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:TR carriage 7 - 2012-05-07.jpg|150px|Carriage No. 7]]\n|Believed [[de Winton]]. Rebuilt by the Talyllyn Railway.\n|c. 1900.\n|13\n|This was ex-[[Penrhyn Quarry Railway]] open carriage 'H'. It operated on the Talyllyn until 1961, and was later used as a tea van at {{stnlnk|Abergynolwyn}}, then as a [[generator wagon]]. During 1985 and 1986 it was completely rebuilt as a wheelchair saloon with guards compartment.<ref>{{harvnb|Bate|2001|p=217}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|8<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3768|title=Carriage 8 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=24 August 2003|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Railway Coach 8 - 2008-06-05.jpg|150px|Carriage No. 8]]\n|[[Penrhyn Quarry Railway]]. Rebuilt by the Talyllyn railway.\n|c. 1900.\n|24\n|This is an open-sided carriage that was originally Penrhyn Quarry Railway open carriage 'P'. It operated on the Talyllyn until 1964, when it was rebuilt from scratch in its current state.\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|11<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3775|title=Carriage 11 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=28 June 2000|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Carriage 11.JPG|150px|Carriage No. 11]]\n|[[Penrhyn Quarry Railway]]. Converted by the Talyllyn Railway\n|Unknown. Converted in 1955.\n|24\n|Open sided\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|12<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3766|title=Carriage 12 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=28 June 2000|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Railway Coach 12 - 2013-05-06.jpg|150px|Carriage No. 12]]\n|Talyllyn Railway\n|1956\n|24\n|Open sided.\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|13<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3773|title=Carriage 13 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=28 June 2000|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Railway Coach 13 - 2008-06-05.jpg|150px|Carriage No. 13]]\n|Talyllyn Railway\n|1957\n|24\n|Open sided.\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|14<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3751|title=Carriage 14 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=28 June 2000|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Railway Coach 14 - 2008-06-05.jpg|150px|Carriage No. 14]]\n|Midland R.C.&W.\n|1892\n|12\n|First class. Ex-[[Glyn Valley Tramway]].\n|- style=\"height:113px\"\n|align=\"center\"|15<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3752|title=Carriage 15 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=28 June 2000|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:TR carriage 15 - 2011-05-14.jpg|150px|Carriage No. 15]]\n|Midland R.C.&W.\n|1902\n|12\n|First class. Ex-[[Glyn Valley Tramway]].\n|}\n\n===Bogie carriages===\n{| class=\"sort wikitable sortable\"\n!Number\n!Image\n!Builder\n!Date built\n!Seats<ref name=summary/>\n!Notes\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|9<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3774|title=Carriage 9 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=24 August 2003|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Railway Coach 9 - 2008-06-05.jpg|150px|Carriage No. 9]]\n|W.G. Allen & Tisdales\n|1954\n|30/40\n|\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|10<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3764|title=Carriage 10 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=28 June 2000|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Railway Coach 10 - 2008-06-05.jpg|150px|Carriage No. 10]]\n|W.G. Allen & Tisdales\n|1954\n|18/24\n|Contains guards compartment.\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|16<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3770|title=Carriage 16 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=28 June 2000|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Railway Coach 16 - 2008-03-02.jpg|150px|Carriage No. 16]]\n|Kerr Stuart & TR\n|1961\n|18/24\n|Contains guards compartment.\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|17<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3753|title=Carriage 17 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=28 June 2000|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Corris coach 17 2005.jpg|150px|Carriage No. 17]]\n|[[Metro Cammell|Metropolitan C.&W.]]\n|1898\n|22\n|Ex-Corris Railway No. 8 and [[Great Western Railway|GWR]] No. 4992. Served as a greenhouse/summerhouse in Gobowen from 1930 to 1958 before being restored by the Talyllyn Railway. \n|-\n|align=\"center\"|18<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3754|title=Carriage 18 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=28 June 2000|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Railway Coach 18 - 2008-08-16.jpg|150px|Carriage No. 18]]\n|Talyllyn Railway\n|1965\n|36/48\n|\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|19<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3779|title=Carriage 19 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=28 June 2000|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Railway Coach 19 - 2008-03-02.jpg|150px|Carriage No. 19]]\n|Talyllyn Railway & Tisdales\n|1969\n|12 1st class, 24/32 3rd class\n|Composite carriage\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|20<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3776|title=Carriage 20 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=28 June 2000|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Railway Coach 20 - 2008-06-05.jpg|150px|Carriage No. 20]]\n|Talyllyn Railway & Tisdales\n|1970\n|32/41\n|Wheelchair saloon.\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|21<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3767|title=Carriage 21 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=28 June 2000|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Railway Coach 21 - 2008-03-02.jpg|150px|Carriage No. 21]]\n|Talyllyn Railway & Tisdales\n|1971\n|32/41\n|Wheelchair saloon. Rebuilt in 2012 and returned to service in July 2013.\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|22<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3772|title=Carriage 22 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=28 June 2000|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Railway Coach 22 - 2008-06-05.jpg|150px|Carriage No. 22]]\n|Talyllyn Railway & Tisdales\n|1972\n|24/32\n|Contains guards compartment.\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|23<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3777|title=Carriage 23 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=28 June 2000|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Railway Coach 23 - 2008-03-02.jpg|150px|Carriage No. 23]]\n|Talyllyn Railway & Tisdales\n|1975\n|36/48\n|\n|}\n\n==Goods wagons==\nThe Talyllyn Railway was primarily constructed for conveying slate. Prior to the beginning of the 20th century, the railway owned over 115 wagons,<ref>{{harvnb|Boyd|1970|p=113}}</ref> mainly [[slate wagon]]s, but also a number of other general and special purpose goods wagons. Some of these survived into the preservation era, and since then a large number of additional wagons have been purchased and built. The following table lists the main types of wagon currently in use:\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Number<ref name=stocklist>{{cite web|url=https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/wagons|title=Talyllyn Railway stock - Wagons|accessdate=5 August 2009|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328155549/https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/wagons|archive-date=28 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n!Image\n!Body type<ref name=stocklist/>\n!Origin\n!Notes\n|-\n|1\n|[[File:Open wagon on Talyllyn Railway - 2008-03-18.jpg|150px|Corris open wagon]]\n|No. 1 Open end door\n|[[Corris Railway]]\n|A {{convert|2|long ton|metric ton}} coal wagon, acquired in 1951 from the Corris Railway.<ref name=Boyd115>{{harvnb|Boyd|1970|pp=115\u2013116}}</ref>\n|- style=\"height:113px\"\n|4\n|\n|No. 1 Open side door\n|Corris Railway\n|A {{convert|1|long ton|metric ton}} coal wagon, acquired in 1951 from the Corris Railway.<ref name=Boyd115/>\n|- style=\"height:113px\"\n|5, 8, 11, 13, 15, 17\n|[[File:Talyllyn Railway wagon 17 - 2009-09-26.jpg|150px|Wagon No. 17]]\n|No. 2 Open end door\n|Talyllyn Railway\n|\n|- style=\"height:113px\"\n|6, 7, 9\n|[[File:Talyllyn Railway wagon 9 - 2009-09-26.jpg|150px|Wagon No. 9]]\n|Underframe only\n|Talyllyn Railway\n|\n|- style=\"height:113px\"\n|16\n|\n|No. 2 Open side door\n|Corris Railway\n|\n|- style=\"height:113px\"\n|19\n|\n|Flat wagon\n|\n|This was converted from the original locomotive No. 5.<ref name=stocklist/>\n|-\n|20, 21, 22, 23, 24\n|[[File:Hopper wagons on Talyllyn Railway - 2009-01-01.jpg|150px|Hopper wagons]]\n|Ballast hopper\n|[[Winchburgh]] Shale Oilworks\n|Four of the five hoppers were acquired from Winchburgh in 1961; the fifth was built by the Talyllyn in 1983.<ref>{{harvnb|Potter|1990|p=209}}</ref>\n|-\n|28\n|[[File:Talyllyn Railway van 28 - 2008-03-18.jpg|150px|MoD covered wagon]]\n|No. 1 Covered van\n|[[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]]\n|Acquired from Trecwn [[Royal Naval Armaments Depot]] in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/node/755|title=RNAD Van arrives at Wharf|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|date=18 December 2007|accessdate=5 August 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928234846/http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/node/755|archive-date=28 September 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|29\n|[[File:Talyllyn Railway van 29 - 2008-03-18.jpg|150px|Tool van]]\n|Tool van\n|\n|\n|- style=\"height:113px\"\n|30, 31, 33\n|\n|Bolster wagon\n|[[Ffestiniog Railway]]\n|Open frame wagons used in pairs to carry timber.<ref name=Boyd115/>\n|- style=\"height:113px\"\n|32, 34, 35\n|\n|Flat wagon\n|Ffestiniog Railway\n|{{convert|3|long ton|metric ton}} wagon, acquired in 1956, regauged from {{RailGauge|1ft11.5in}} gauge.<ref name=Boyd115/>\n|- style=\"height:113px\"\n|36\n|\n|No. 1 Flat wagon with crane\n|[[Bowaters Paper Railway|Bowaters Railway]]\n|Acquired in 1971 and known as the ''Boflat''.<ref>{{harvnb|Bate|2001|p=160}}</ref> This was fitted with a crane in January 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/node/784|title=Testing the New Boflat Crane|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|date=5 February 2009|accessdate=5 August 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928234921/http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/node/784|archive-date=28 September 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|- style=\"height:113px\"\n|37\n|[[File:Boflat wagon on Talyllyn Railway - 2008-03-18.jpg|150px|MoD flat wagon with crane]]\n|No. 2 Flat wagon with crane\n|Bowaters Railway\n|\n|-\n|40, 41, 42, 43, 50, 52, 53, 54, 55\n|[[File:Tipper wagon on Talyllyn Railway - 2008-03-18.jpg|150px|Tipper wagon]]\n|Tipper wagon\n|Cefn Coch quarry\n|A set of {{RailGauge|2ft6in}} gauge wagons obtained in 1975.<ref>{{harvnb|Bate|2001|p=149}}</ref>\n|-\n|60, 61, 62\n|[[File:Flat Wagon on Talyllyn Railway - 2008-03-18.jpg|150px|MoD flat wagon]]\n|Flat wagon\n|Ministry of Defence\n|\n|-\n|70\n|[[File:Talyllyn Railway van 70 - 2009-01-01.jpg|150px|Bogie brake van]]\n|Bogie brake van\n|Ministry of Defence\n|Known as Boadicea, and repainted into green livery in January 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/news/2013-january-2627-work-pendre|title=2013 - January 26/27 Work at Pendre|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|date=27 January 2013|accessdate=7 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304191526/http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/news/2013-january-2627-work-pendre|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|- style=\"height:113px\"\n|71, 72\n|\n|Bogie flat wagon\n|Ministry of Defence\n|\n|-\n|101, 136, 164, 178\n|[[File:Slate wagon on Talyllyn Railway - 2008-03-18.jpg|150px|Slate wagon]]\n|Slate wagons\n|Talyllyn Railway\n|Three 2-bar and one 3-bar wooden slate wagons, owned by the [[Narrow Gauge Railway Museum]].\n|-\n|117\n|[[File:Talyllyn Railway wagon 117 - 2009-01-01.jpg|150px|Incline wagon]]\n|Incline open\n|Talyllyn Railway\n|Original general purpose wagon, built with sheet iron sides and designed to prevent spillages while hauled on the Abergynolwyn village incline,<ref>{{harvnb|Boyd|1988|p=299}}</ref> owned by the Narrow Gauge Railway Museum.\n|-\n|146\n|[[File:Talyllyn Railway van 146 - 2008-03-18.jpg|150px|Covered van]]\n|No. 2 Covered van\n|Talyllyn Railway\n|Original van, owned by the Narrow Gauge Railway Museum.\n|- style=\"height:113px\"\n|N\n|\n|Mail Waggon{{refn|group=note|name=note_e|The Corris Railway used the alternative spelling of ''waggon'' for its rolling stock, and this has been applied here.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ngrm.org.uk/Collections/PublicCarriers/CorrisRailway/CR024|title=Corris mail waggon CR024|publisher=[[Narrow Gauge Railway Museum]]|accessdate=22 September 2012}}</ref>}}\n|Corris Railway\n|Owned by the Narrow Gauge Railway Museum.\n|}\n\n==Narrow Gauge Railway Museum rolling stock==\n{{Main|Narrow Gauge Railway Museum}}\n\nThe Narrow Gauge Railway Museum is a purpose-built museum dedicated to narrow gauge railways situated on the [[Tywyn Wharf railway station|Tywyn Wharf station]]. It owns several wagons formerly in use on the railway (listed above), as well as rolling stock and other artefacts from other narrow gauge railways around the world. The wagons are still used occasionally on the Talyllyn.\n\n==Liveries==\nThe standard [[livery#Modern usage|livery]] for locomotives on the Talyllyn is deep bronze green,<ref name=livery>{{cite web|title=Enthusiast's Introduction|url=https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/enthusiasts/enthusiasts-introduction|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|accessdate=11 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090827220439/http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/details/locos|archive-date=27 August 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> lined in black and yellow, although since the 1980s there has been a policy of varying some of the liveries for a period of time.\n\nThe liveries carried by the steam locomotives as of 2018 are as follows:-\n\n*No. 1: [[Indian red (color)|Indian Red]].<ref name=BBC_Jan2015>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-30719626|title=Talyllyn steam locomotives get secret 150th paint job|publisher=BBC News|date=8 January 2015|accessdate=8 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150108075008/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-north-west-wales-30719626|archive-date=8 January 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> This is believed to be the livery applied to Nos. 1 and 2 when first built.<ref>{{harvnb|Fuller|2014|p=27}}</ref>\n*No. 2: Indian Red.<ref name=BBC_Jan2015/>\n*No. 3: Standard Talyllyn green with standard lining. Burnished motion and Black background to Builders/Name/Number plates.<ref name=No3/>\n*No. 4: Standard Talyllyn green with standard lining. Burnished motion and Black background to Builders/Name/Number plates.<ref name=No4/>\n*No. 6: RAF blue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/news/no-6-douglas-gets-centenary-birthday-makeover|title=No.6 'Douglas' gets a Centenary Birthday makeover|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|date=23 February 2018|accessdate=23 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224052938/http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/news/no6-douglas-gets-centenary-birthday-makeover|archive-date=24 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*No. 7: Standard Talyllyn green with standard lining. Burnished motion and Black background to Builders/Name/Number plates.<ref name=No7/>\n\nThe vintage rolling stock and the carriages built for the line after preservation are cherry red, lined with deep bronze green. Additionally, the railway has preserved rolling stock from other railways. These retain their original liveries.\n\nThe Corris coach (Talyllyn No. 17) and brake van (Talyllyn No. 6) are brown lined with gold leaf and the two [[Glyn Valley Tramway]] coaches (Talyllyn Nos. 14 and 15) are green lined with white.<ref name=livery/>\n\n==In fiction==\n{{main|Skarloey Railway#Locomotives|l1=Skarloey Railway locomotives}}\nMost of the locomotives have an equivalent counterpart on the fictional [[Skarloey Railway]], a railway that forms part of ''[[The Railway Series]]'' of books by [[Rev. W Awdry]] and his son  [[Christopher Awdry|Christopher]]. The Rev. W Awdry visited the Talyllyn Railway on a family holiday in the early days of preservation and became involved as a volunteer soon afterwards.<ref>Potter, page 89</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2|refs=\n<ref name=\"IRS 15EL\">{{irs-el |el=15}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n* {{Cite book|last=Bate|first=John|title=The Chronicles of Pendre Sidings|publisher=RailRomances|year=2001|isbn=1-900622-05-X|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Boyd|first=James I.C.|title=Narrow Gauge Railways in Mid Wales|edition=2nd|publisher=Oakwood Press|year=1970|isbn=0-85361-024-X|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Boyd |first=James I.C.|title=The Tal-y-llyn Railway |publisher=Wild Swan Publications Ltd |year=1988|isbn=0-906867-46-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Welsh Narrow Gauge in the 1980s |last=Cox |first=David |publisher=Battenhall Books |year=1983 |isbn=0-9508577-0-X|ref=}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Fuller|first=Martin|title=Talyllyn & Corris Steam Locomotives|volume=Volume 1: Pre-preservation and Manufacturers|publisher=Sara Eade|year=2014|isbn=978-0-9565652-5-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Hatherhill|first=Ann and Gordon |title=Narrow Gauge & Industrial Album |publisher=RCL Publications|year=2004|isbn=0-9538763-5-7|ref=}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Talyllyn Railway |last1=Mitchell|first1=David J.|last2=Eyres|first2=Terry |publisher=Past and Present Publishing Ltd |year=2005 |isbn=1-85895-125-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|title=The Talyllyn Railway in Colour|last=Morland|first=R. J.|year=2005|publisher=R. J. Morland|isbn=0-9549893-0-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Potter|first=David|title=The Talyllyn Railway|publisher=David St John Thomas|year=1990|isbn=0-946537-50-X|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Ransom |first=P.J.G |title=Narrow Gauge Steam: Its origins and world-wide development |publisher=Oxford Publishing Co |year=1996 |isbn=0-86093-533-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor1-last=Rolt|editor1-first=L.T.C.|title=Talyllyn Century|publisher=David & Charles|year=1965|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Thomas |first=Cliff |title=The Narrow Gauge in Britain and Ireland |year=2002 |publisher=Atlantic Publishing |isbn=1-902827-05-8 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/narrowgaugeinbri0000thom }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category multi|Steam locomotives of the Talyllyn Railway|Diesel locomotives of the Talyllyn Railway|Carriages of the Talyllyn Railway|Wagons of the Talyllyn Railway|width=25em|delimiter=&nbsp;or<BR>}}\n*[http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/ Talyllyn Railway website]\n*[http://www.ngrm.org.uk/ Narrow Gauge Railway Museum]\n\n{{Talyllyn Railway}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Talyllyn Railway rolling stock}}\n[[Category:Talyllyn Railway|Rolling stock]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom narrow gauge rolling stock]]\n[[Category:Wales-related lists]]\n[[Category:British railway-related lists]]\n[[Category:Wales transport-related lists]]\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Wales]]\n", "text_old": "{{use British English|date=August 2019}}\n{{short description|List of rolling stock used on the Talyllyn Railway in Wales}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n\n[[File:Talyllyn Cavalcade - 2018-06-16.webm|thumb|right|thumbtime=9|Video showing all steam and diesel locomotives departing Tywyn Wharf]]\nThis is a list of past and present [[rolling stock]] used on the [[Talyllyn Railway]] ({{lang-cy|Rheilffordd Talyllyn}}), a {{RailGauge|2ft3in}} [[narrow gauge railway|narrow gauge]] [[heritage railway|preserved]] [[railway]] line running for {{convert|7.25|mi|km}}<ref name=TRWEB>{{cite web|title=About the Talyllyn Railway|url=http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/about|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|accessdate=5 August 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090809115807/http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/about|archive-date=9 August 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> from [[Tywyn]] on the [[Mid-Wales]] coast to [[Nant Gwernol railway station|Nant Gwernol]] near the village of [[Abergynolwyn]]. The line was opened in 1866 to carry [[slate]] from the quarries at [[Bryn Eglwys]] to Tywyn, and was the first narrow gauge railway in Britain authorised by [[Act of Parliament#United Kingdom|Act of Parliament]] to carry passengers using steam haulage.<ref>{{harvnb|Mitchell|Eyres|2005|p=7}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Boyd|1988|p=44}}</ref> Despite severe under-investment,<ref>{{harvnb|Rolt|1965|p=50}}</ref> the line remained open, and in 1951 it became the first railway in the world to be preserved as a heritage railway by volunteers.<ref>{{harvnb|Thomas|2002|p=32}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Ransom|1996|p=139}}</ref>\n\nWhen first opened, the railway owned two steam locomotives, ''[[Talyllyn (locomotive)|Talyllyn]]'' and ''[[Dolgoch (locomotive)|Dolgoch]]'', and five carriages, including one brake van. There were no additions to the rolling stock until the line was taken over in 1951.{{refn|name=note_a|group=note|There is evidence that during the 1910s, [[Henry Haydn Jones]], the owner of the railway at the time, requested estimates for a new locomotive for the railway.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Newing|first=Don|date=December 2010|title=The Talyllyn Locomotive No. 3 That Never Was|journal=Talyllyn News|issue=228|page=31|issn=0300-3272}}</ref> However, no purchase was made.}} Two ex-[[Corris Railway]] locomotives were then purchased from [[British Rail]]ways, and subsequent additions have brought the total up to six steam locomotives, four diesels and twenty-three carriages.\n\n== Locomotives ==\nThe railway has six steam locomotives for passenger trains and five diesel locomotives that usually haul only works trains. It is unusual for all steam locomotives to be operable at one time, as there is usually at least one locomotive undergoing overhaul.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/node/661 |title=Talyllyn website \u2013 100% availability |publisher=Talyllyn Railway Company |accessdate=5 August 2009 |date=29 August 2007 |author=Higginson, Karen |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221203929/http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/node/661 |archive-date=21 December 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Steam locomotives ===\n{{Hatnote|For technical details about each locomotive, see the relevant locomotive article.}}\n{| class=\"sort wikitable\"\n!Number\n!Name\n!Image\n!width=\"82pt\"|[[Whyte notation]]\n!Builder\n!Works number\n!Date built\n!Current status<br>(as of 19 December 2018)\n!''[[Railway Series]]/[[Thomas & Friends]]'' equivalent<ref name=\"Sodor\">{{cite book|title=Sodor: Reading Between the Lines|last=Awdry|first=Christopher|author-link=Christopher Awdry|publisher=Sodor Enterprises|year=2005|pages=12\u201314|title-link=List of Railway Series books#Sodor: Reading Between the Lines}}</ref>\n{{TR steam locos|\n|number=1\n|name=Talyllyn\n|image=Tal-y-Llyn (19435419666).jpg\n|alt=Talyllyn at Tywyn Wharf\n|whyte={{Whyte|0-4-2|ST}}<ref name=No1>{{cite web|title=No. 1 'Talyllyn'|url=https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-1-talyllyn|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|accessdate=20 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181220230637/https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-1-talyllyn|archive-date=20 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|builder=[[Fletcher, Jennings & Co.|Fletcher,&nbsp;Jennings<br />&&nbsp;Co.]], Whitehaven<ref name=No1/>\n|worksno=42<ref name=No1/>\n|built=1864<ref name=No1/>\n|status= Undergoing overhaul.<ref name=No1/>\n|rseries=[[Skarloey]]\n[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Minor Characters|''Rusty's Ghost Engine'']] <small>''(Thomas & Friends only)</small>\n|notes=One of two original locomotives, it was built as an {{whyte|0-4-0|ST}} without a cab. By 1866, trailing wheels had been added to improve stability, and it had a cab installed at the same time.<ref name=No1/> It was named after the railway.}}\n\n{{TR steam locos\n|number=2\n|name=Dolgoch\n|image=Dolgoch (18838965524).jpg\n|alt=Dolgoch at Tywyn Wharf\n|whyte={{Whyte|0-4-0|WT}}<ref name=No2>{{cite web|title=No. 2 'Dolgoch'|url=https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-2-dolgoch|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|accessdate=20 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181024073736/https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-2-dolgoch|archive-date=24 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|builder=Fletcher,&nbsp;Jennings<br />&&nbsp;Co., Whitehaven<ref name=No2/>\n|worksno=63<ref name=No2/>\n|built=1866<ref name=No2/>\n|status=In service<ref name=No2/>\n|rseries=[[Rheneas]]\n[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Minor Characters|''Smudger'']] <small>''(Thomas & Friends only)</small>\n|notes=The second original locomotive. Like ''Talyllyn'', it was built without a cab, though one was subsequently added. It was named after the intermediate station and local waterfalls, though after the [[Second Boer War|Boer War]], it carried the name ''[[Pretoria]]'' for several years. In 2011 it received a new boiler, and returned to steam in time for the 60th anniversary celebrations of the preservation society on 14 May.}}\n\n{{TR steam locos\n|number=3\n|name=Sir Haydn\n|image=Talyllyn Railway No. 3 Sir Haydn - 2018-06-16.jpg\n|alt=Sir Haydn at Abergynolywn\n|whyte={{Whyte|0-4-2|ST}}<ref name=No3>{{cite web|title=No. 3 'Sir Haydn'|url=https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-3-sir-haydn|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|accessdate=20 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701082555/https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-3-sir-haydn|archive-date=1 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|builder=Hughes,<br /> [[Falcon Works]],<br /> [[Loughborough]]<ref name=No3/>\n|worksno=323<ref name=No3/>\n|built=1878<ref name=No3/>\n|status=In service<ref name=No3/>\n|rseries=[[Sir Handel]]\n[[List of Thomas & Friends narrow-gauge engines#Minor Characters|''Proteus'']] <small>''(Thomas & Friends only)</small>\n\n[[Mid Sodor Railway#Locomotives|''Albert'']] <small>''(Railway Series only)</small>\n|notes=An ex-[[Corris Railway]] locomotive, purchased in 1951 and subsequently named after [[Henry Haydn Jones|Sir Henry Haydn Jones]], owner of the railway prior to preservation. Following the expiry of its 10-year boiler ticket in early 2012, the loco was stored out of use at the Corris Railway until April 2013, when it commenced a tour of various railway sites in England to help raise funds for its overhaul. In February 2015 it was moved back to the Talyllyn. In Autumn 2015 it was sent to the [[Vale of Rheidol Railway]]'s new workshop in [[Aberystwyth]] for its overhaul to start. It returned to service in 2018, in time for its 140th birthday.}}\n\n{{TR steam locos\n|number=4\n|name=Edward Thomas\n|image=Edward Thomas (13796797195).jpg\n|alt=Edward Thomas at Tywyn Wharf\n|whyte={{Whyte|0-4-2|ST}}<ref name=No4>{{cite web|title=No. 4 'Edward Thomas'|url=https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-4-edward-thomas|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|accessdate=20 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181220230933/https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-4-edward-thomas|archive-date=20 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|builder=[[Kerr Stuart]],<br>[[Stoke-on-Trent]]<ref name=No4/>\n|worksno=4047<ref name=No4/>\n|built=1921<ref name=No4/>\n|status=In service<ref name=No4/>\n|rseries=[[Peter Sam]]\n|notes=The second ex-Corris Railway locomotive, also purchased in 1951 and subsequently named after the general manager of the line prior to preservation. It was fitted with a [[Giesl ejector]] between 1958 and 1969.<ref>{{harvnb|Potter|1990|p=198}}</ref> Received a new boiler in 2004.}}\n\n{{TR steam locos\n|number=6\n|name=Douglas\n|image=No. 6 Douglas in RAF blue - 2018-02-21.jpg\n|alt=Douglas at Tywyn Wharf\n|whyte={{Whyte|0-4-0|WT}}<ref name=No6>{{cite web|title=No. 6 'Douglas'/'Duncan'|url=https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-6-douglas-duncan|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|accessdate=20 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701082614/https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-6-douglas-duncan|archive-date=1 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|builder=[[Andrew Barclay Sons & Co.|Andrew Barclay]], [[Kilmarnock]]<ref name=No6/>\n|worksno=1431<ref name=No6/>\n|built=1918<ref name=No6/>\n|status=In service<ref name=No6/>\n|rseries=[[Duncan (fictional locomotive)|Duncan]]\n|notes=A \"Modified E Class\", built for the depot railway serving [[RAF Calshot]].<ref>{{harvnb|Boyd|1970|pp=100\u2013101}}</ref> It was donated to the Talyllyn in 1953, regauged from {{RailGauge|2ft}} gauge and named after Douglas Abelson, who donated the locomotive.<ref>{{harvnb|Morland|2005|p=21}}</ref>\nReturned to service July 2013 as 'Douglas' in bright red and black border livery. Repainted to RAF blue livery in March 2018.}}\n\n{{TR steam locos\n|number=7\n|name=Tom Rolt\n|image=Tom Rolt (14726150433).jpg\n|alt=Tom Rolt at Tywyn Wharf\n|whyte={{Whyte|0-4-2|T}}<ref name=No7>{{cite web|title=No. 7 'Tom Rolt'|url=https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-7-tom-rolt|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|accessdate=20 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181220230941/https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/locomotives/no-7-tom-rolt|archive-date=20 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|builder=Talyllyn Railway<ref name=No7/>\n|worksno=none given<ref name=No7/>\n|built=1991<ref name=No7/>{{refn|name=TomRolt|group=note|This refers to the year the locomotive was built by the Talyllyn. The Bord na M\u00f3na locomotive used for some of the constituent parts was built in 1949.}}\n|status=In service<ref name=No7/>\n|rseries=[[Skarloey Railway#Locomotives|Ivo Hugh]] <small>(Railway Series Only)</small>\n|notes=This locomotive was built by the Talyllyn Railway using components from a [[Bord na M\u00f3na]] (Irish Peat Board) Andrew Barclay locomotive. It was originally intended to give it the jocular name ''Irish Pete''. However, prior to completion, it was decided to name it in honour of [[L.T.C. Rolt]], one of the founders of the Talyllyn Railway Preservation Society.}} Returned to service in 2019 following a ten-yearly overhaul.\n|}\n\n=== Diesel locomotives ===\n{| class=\"sort wikitable\"\n!Number\n!Name\n!Image\n!Type\n!Builder\n!Date built\n!Power ([[Horsepower|hp]])<ref name=Bate257>{{harvnb|Bate|2001|p=257}}</ref>\n!Wheel diameter<ref name=Bate257/>\n!''Railway Series/Thomas & Friends'' equivalent<ref name=\"Sodor\"/>\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|5\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''Midlander''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Railway Midlander No 5.jpg|150px|Midlander at Pendre]]\n|align=\"center\" | {{whyte|4w|DM}}\n|[[Ruston & Hornsby]]\n|1941<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/news/outing-no-5s-70th-birthday|title=An Outing for No. 5's 70th Birthday|date=9 February 2010|accessdate=21 September 2012|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401132720/http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/news/outing-no-5s-70th-birthday|archive-date=1 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|48\n|{{convert|1|ft|6|in|abbr=on}}\n|''[[Rusty (locomotive)|Rusty]]''\n|-\n|colspan=6|This locomotive was purchased in 1957 from Jee's quarries at [[Hartshill]],<ref>{{harvnb|Potter|1990|p=201}}</ref> and contains parts that were cannibalised off an identical locomotive. It was named after the [[English Midlands|Midlands]] area group of the preservation society that donated the locomotive.\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|9\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''Alf''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Railway No 9 Alf - 2008-03-18.jpg|150px|Alf at Pendre]]\n|align=\"center\" | {{whyte|0-4-0|DM}}\n|[[Hunslet Engine Co.]]\n|1950\n|75\n|{{convert|2|ft|abbr=on}}\n|''[[Fred (locomotive)|Fred]]'' <small>(Railway Series Only)</small>\n|-\n|colspan=6|This is an ex-[[National Coal Board]] locomotive, from [[Huncoat]] colliery in [[Lancashire]].<ref name=Potter202/> It was named after [[Alfred Robens, Baron Robens of Woldingham|Alf Robens]], chairman of the National Coal Board.<ref>{{harvnb|Morland|2005|p=13}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|11\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''Trecwn''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Railway No 11 Trecwn - 2018-06-16.jpg|150px|Trecwn at Nant Gwernol]]\n|align=\"center\" | {{whyte|4w|DH}}\n|[[Ernest E. Baguley|Baguley]]\n|1983-84<ref name=\"IRS 15EL\" />\n|99\n|610mm\n|\n|-\n|colspan=6|One of three Baguley diesels that were purchased from [[RNAD Trecwn]] in South Wales in 2008. These were originally bought by a consortium of volunteers, but have since been purchased from this group by the railway. This loco was originally numbered T&nbsp;0006&nbsp;00&nbsp;NZ&nbsp;32 (BD&nbsp;3764)<ref name=\"IRS 15EL\" /><ref name=otherlocos>{{Cite web|url=https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/enthusiasts/locomotives|title=Locomotives|accessdate=11 October 2019|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328155509/https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/enthusiasts/locomotives|archive-date=28 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and entered service on the Talyllyn in 2014.\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|12\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''St. Cadfan''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:No. 12 St. Cadfan - 2018-02-21.jpg|150px|St. Cadfan at Wharf]]\n|align=\"center\" | {{whyte|4w|DH}}\n|Baguley\n|1983-84<ref name=\"IRS 15EL\" />\n|99\n|610mm\n|\n|-\n|colspan=6|The second of the three Baguley diesels that were purchased from [[RNAD Trecwn]] in South Wales in 2008.{{refn|name=note_d|group=note|The third loco, formerly T 0009 00 NZ 35 (BD 3781), will not operate on the railway, but is being used for spares.}} This loco was originally numbered BD 3779<ref name=\"IRS 15EL\" /><ref name=\"otherlocos\"/> and named after [[St Cadfan's Church, Tywyn|St Cadfan's Church]] in Tywyn.\n|}\n\n=== Self-propelled engineering plant ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Name\n!Image\n!Type\n!Builder\n!Date built\n|- style=\"height:113px\"\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''Toby''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Motor Trolley \"Toby\" on Talyllyn Railway - 2008-03-18.jpg|100px|Permanent Way Trolley]]\n|Permanent Way Trolley\n|John Bate<ref name=Toby>{{Cite web|url=https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/news/toby-returns|title='Toby' Returns!|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|accessdate=19 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619212546/https://www.talyllyn.co.uk/news/toby-returns|archive-date=19 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|1954<ref name=Toby/>\n|-\n|colspan=3|Small trolley used by engineers for transportation to worksites. Built from a second hand [[Austin 7]] engine and gearbox, mounted on a custom-made chassis.<ref>{{harvnb|Bate|2001|p=42}}</ref> It was damaged in a shunting accident in 2008 and taken out of service, but returned to use in 2019.<ref name=Toby/>\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"| -\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Tamper.JPG|150px|Matisa ballast tamper]]\n|[[Ballast tamper]]\n|Matisa<ref name=Matisa>{{cite web|url=http://www.matisa.ch/|title=Manufacturer's website|access-date=13 March 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080321003522/http://www.matisa.ch/|archive-date=21 March 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|1990\n|-\n|colspan=3|Rail mounted track tamper. Parts of two ex-[[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|MOD]] [[standard gauge]] tampers were acquired in 1989 and one complete machine was assembled and commissioned on 26 June 1990.<ref>{{harvnb|Bate|2001|pp=230\u2013231}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"| -\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Flail mover.JPG|150px|Flail mower]]\n|Flail Mower\n|Talyllyn Railway\n|1998\n|-\n|colspan=3|Rail mounted self-propelled vehicle used to clear lineside vegetation.<ref>{{harvnb|Morland|2005|p=40}}</ref> Designed by John Bate (Chief Engineer 1963-1994) and built from chassis components from two [[Ruston (engine builder)|Ruston & Hornsby]] locomotives, the framing and motor components of a [[Smalley (excavator)|Smalley]] excavator, the flail mechanism and cab from a McConnel [[flail mower]] and a new [[Perkins Engines|Perkins]] diesel power unit.<ref>{{harvnb|Bate|2001|pp=248\u2013249}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Former locomotives===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Number\n!Name\n!Image\n!Type\n!Builder\n!Date built\n!Power ([[Horsepower|hp]])\n!Year with-<br />drawn\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|5\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''\"The Lawnmower\"''<ref name=Bate33>{{harvnb|Bate|2001|p=33}}</ref><ref group=note>Names in inverted commas refer to unofficial nick-names, not formally applied.</ref>\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|\n|align=\"center\" | {{whyte|4w|PH}}\n|[[David Curwen]]\n|1952\n|20<ref>{{harvnb|Boyd|1970|p=98}}</ref>\n|1953\n|-\n|colspan=5|This lightweight locomotive was built by member David Curwen using a [[Ford Model T]] engine and transmission from L.T.C Rolt's [[narrowboat]] and the wheels from a Talyllyn Railway [[slate wagon]]. It worked the Fridays-only winter passenger service until 1953,<ref name=RMJan2013>{{cite magazine|date=January 2013|title=Historic Talyllyn loco to be resurrected|magazine=[[The Railway Magazine]]|page=93}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Boyd|1970|p=99}}</ref> when it was taken out of use with a failed gearbox. It was dismantled in 1954,<ref name=Bate33/> and converted to flat wagon No. 19 (see below).<ref name=stocklist/> It is proposed to rebuild it as a memorial to David Curwen, using a replacement engine and bodywork.<ref name=RMJan2013/>\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|7\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''\"Charley's Ant\"''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|\n|align=\"center\" | 4-2-0\n|Talyllyn Railway\n|1954\n|\n|c.1958\n|-\n|colspan=5|A Mercury [[tractor]] that had been adapted to push standard gauge rolling stock by the addition of a [[buffer beam]]. It was further adapted in 1954 for use on the Talyllyn, and later converted to run on paraffin instead of petrol.<ref>{{harvnb|Boyd|1970|p=102}}</ref> It was little used after 1958 and later scrapped. It was nicknamed after Charles Uren, the railway's chief engineer.<ref name=Potter202/>\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|8\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''Merseysider''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Merseysider at Nant Gwernol - 2006-03-05.jpg|150px|Merseysider at Nant Gwernol]]\n|align=\"center\" | {{whyte|4w|DH}}\n|Ruston & Hornsby\n|1964\n|50\n|2016\n|-\n|colspan=6|This was originally built using parts from three {{RailGauge|3ft}} gauge locomotives from Park Gate [[steelworks]] in [[Rotherham]], acquired in 1969.<ref name=Potter202>{{harvnb|Potter|1990|p=202}}</ref> The superstructure was replaced c. 2000. It has a Dowty [[Transmission (mechanics)#Hydrostatic|hydrostatic transmission]]. The name was chosen by the donor of the locomotive.<ref>{{harvnb|Morland|2005|p=41}}</ref> This locomotive was sold in 2016. \n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|10\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''Bryn Eglwys''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Railway No 10 Bryn Eglwys - 2009-03-01.jpg|150px|Bryn Eglwys at Wharf]]\n|align=\"center\" | {{whyte|4w|DH}}\n|[[Motor Rail]]\n|1985\n|110\n|2014\n|-\n|colspan=5|This was originally a {{RailGauge|2ft6in}} gauge National Coal Board locomotive from Hem Heath colliery near [[Stoke-on-Trent]].<ref>{{cite book|chapter=Engineering Report |title=Talyllyn News|edition= issue 175 (September 1997) |page=6}}</ref> It arrived on the Talyllyn September 1997,<ref name=otherlocos/> and was re-painted into standard Talyllyn livery during summer 2005. The locomotive was named after the [[Bryn Eglwys]] slate quarries. The loco was sold to the [[North Gloucestershire Railway]],<ref name=CouncilRep13>{{Cite web|url=http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/internal/arrc-14c|title=Report of the Council for 2013|accessdate=22 September 2014|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924043712/http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/internal/arrc-14c|archive-date=24 September 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> and left the railway in August 2014 when the first Baguley loco entered service.\n|}\n\n=== Visiting locomotives ===\n{{As of|2015}} there have only been two visiting locomotives capable of running on the Talyllyn Railway's unusual gauge. These are [[Motor Rail]] Simplex diesel No. 5 ''Alan Meaden'' and [[Winson Engineering]] and Drayton Designs No. 7 ''Tattoo'' class design<ref name=TRCORRISNEWS>{{cite web|title=Announcing the Corris Weekend & CR 7 Visit|url=http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/news/corris-railway-no-7-visit|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|date=6 October 2011|accessdate=6 October 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111023002213/http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/news/corris-railway-no-7-visit|archive-date=23 October 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> similar to the Talyllyn's No. 4. Both these are locomotives from the Corris Railway.\n\nIn July 2015 a gala was held to mark the railway's 150th anniversary, and two {{railgauge|23.5in}} gauge locomotives visited the railway: [[George England and Co.]] locomotive ''[[Festiniog Railway 0-4-0TT|Prince]]'' from the [[Ffestiniog Railway]] and [[Hunslet Engine Company]] ''[[Russell (locomotive)|Russell]]'' from the [[Welsh Highland Heritage Railway]], both in [[Porthmadog]]. Two lengths of temporary track were laid at {{stnlnk|Tywyn Wharf}} to allow the locomotives to operate over a short distance.\n\nIn July 2016, another gala was held, with three visiting locos, all built by Fletcher, Jennings and Co. Together with ''Talyllyn'' and ''Dolgoch'', this was an assembly of all five surviving locos in the UK built by this firm.<ref>{{Cite news|title=150th anniversary of Dolgoch finale|publisher=Cambrian News|date=11 July 2016|url=http://www.cambrian-news.co.uk/article.cfm?id=106273&headline=150th+anniversary+of+Dolgoch+finale&sectionIs=news&searchyear=2016|accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref> As with the previous gala, temporary track was laid due to the differing gauges.<ref name=SR2016>{{Cite web|title=Five engines, three gauges, one railway|url=https://www.steamrailway.co.uk/steamnews/2016/7/15/five-engines-three-gauges-one-railway|publisher=Steam Railway|date=15 July 2016|accessdate=5 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007230417/http://www.steamrailway.co.uk/steamnews/2016/7/15/five-engines-three-gauges-one-railway|archive-date=7 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> One of the locomotives, ''[[Rolling stock of the Bluebell Railway|Captain Baxter]]'', ran on a short section of [[standard gauge]] track. The other two Fletcher Jennings locomotives, ''William Finlay'' and ''[[Townsend Hook]]'' were static exhibits only, and are therefore not listed below. ''William Finlay'' remained at Tywyn after the event and is now on display at the [[Narrow Gauge Railway Museum]].\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Number\n!Name\n!Image\n!&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Type&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n!Builder\n!Date built\n!''[[Railway Series]]/[[Thomas & Friends]]'' equivalent<ref name=\"Sodor\" />\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|5\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''Alan Meaden''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Corris No 5 - 2012-05-07.jpg|150px|Alan Meaden on the Corris Railway]]\n|{{whyte|4w|DM}}\n|[[Motor Rail]] Simplex\n|1965\n|-\n|colspan=3|A former {{RailGauge|2ft}} gauge diesel from Staveley Lime Products, Hindlow, Derbyshire, named in honour of the Corris Society's founder. It visited the Talyllyn in 1983 and 1990.<ref>{{harvnb|Bate|2001|p=205}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|7\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|(unnamed)\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Corris loco 7 on Talyllyn - 2011-10-23 (cropped).jpg|150px|Corris No. 7]]\n|{{Whyte|0-4-2|ST}}\n|[[Winson Engineering]] and Drayton Designs\n|2005\n|-\n|colspan=3|Built for the Corris Railway, based on the Kerr Stuart \"Tattoo\" class design of Corris No. 4. It visited the Talyllyn in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Corris No 7 Visit - 7th and 8th October 2011|url=http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/news/corris-no-7-visit-7th-and-8th-october-2011|publisher=Talyllyn Railway|date=8 October 2011|accessdate=8 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111023002208/http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/news/corris-no-7-visit-7th-and-8th-october-2011|archive-date=23 October 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|2\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''Prince''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Prince at Tywyn Wharf - 2015-07-04.jpg|150px|Prince]]\n|{{Whyte|0-4-0|TT}}{{refn|name=note_tt|group=note|TT denotes a [[tank locomotive]] with additional [[Tender (rail)|tender]].}}\n|George England and Co.\n|1864<ref name=FFR>{{Quine-FR}}</ref>{{refn|name=note_fr|group=note|Some sources state that ''Prince'' was built in 1863.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ffestiniograilway.org.uk/full_article?a=ffestiniog-locomotives|title=Ffestiniog locomotives|publisher=Ffestiniog Railway Society|date=1 January 2014|accessdate=9 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924012045/http://www.ffestiniograilway.org.uk/full_article?a=ffestiniog-locomotives|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live|series=[[Mid Sodor Railway#Locomotives|Duke]] [[Bertram]] <small>(Thomas & Friends only]] </small>}}</ref>}}\n|colspan=3|''Prince'' was built in 1863 for the [[Ffestiniog Railway]] and is the oldest FR locomotive still in operating condition. It has spent all of its working life on the FR, but in 2015 ran on a short length of {{RailGauge|1ft11.5in}} gauge track laid at Tywyn Wharf station as part of the TR's 150th. anniversary celebrations.\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|(unnumbered)\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''Russell''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Russell (19435415896).jpg|150px|Russell]]\n|{{Whyte|2-6-2|T}}\n|Hunslet Engine Co.\n|1906\n|rseries=[[Skarloey Railway#Locomotives|''Duke'']]\n|-\n|colspan=3|Built in 1906 for the [[North Wales Narrow Gauge Railways|NWNGR]], ''Russell'' later ran on the [[Welsh Highland Railway]]. After the WHR closed in 1937 it moved to the [[Brymbo Ironworks railway]] and then in 1946 to [[Purbeck Ball Clay|Fayle's Tramway]] in Dorset. It was rescued for preservation in 1954 and between 1955, and 1965 ''Russell'' was on display as a static exhibit outside the [[Narrow Gauge Railway Museum]] at Tywyn. Since 1965 the locomotive has belonged the [[Welsh Highland Heritage Railway|WHHR]]. It visited Tywyn again in 2015 as part of the TR's 150th. anniversary celebrations.\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|3\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|''Captain Baxter''\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|[[File:Captain Baxter at Tywyn Wharf - 2016-07-02.jpg|150px|Captain Baxter]]\n|{{Whyte|0-4-0|T}}\n|Fletcher, Jennings and Co.\n|1877\n|-\n|colspan=3|A standard gauge locomotive, built in 1877 for the [[Betchworth railway station#Betchworth Quarry Railways|Betchworth Quarry Railways]] in Surrey. It is persevered by the [[Bluebell Railway]] in West Sussex.\n|}\n\n==Carriages==\nThe Talyllyn railway has a total of 23 [[Passenger car (rail)|carriages]]. The first five are the original carriages built for the railway, though they were not provided with numbers until preservation in 1951. After that time, the remaining carriages were built by the railway or acquired from elsewhere.<ref name=summary>{{Cite web|url=http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/details/summary|title=Talyllyn Railway Carriage Summary|accessdate=5 August 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100312044754/http://www.talyllyn.co.uk/details/summary|archive-date=12 March 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> With the exception of ex-Corris carriage No. 17, all the [[bogie]] coaches were built for the railway after preservation; the smaller four wheeled coaches are generally older.\n\nAll the stock is third class only, unless otherwise stated. Where two figures are given for the number of seats, the larger figure is the maximum number of passengers than can be carried in a heavily loaded train.\n\n===Four wheeled carriages===\n{| class=\"sort wikitable sortable\"\n!Number\n!Image\n!Builder\n!Date built\n!Seats<ref name=summary/>\n!Notes\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3746|title=Carriage 1 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=24 August 2003|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Carriage 1.JPG|150px|Carriage No. 1]]\n|[[Brown, Marshalls and Co. Ltd.|Brown, Marshalls]]\n|1866\n|18\n|This was originally a first class carriage; it is now third class.<ref name=Boyd282>{{harvnb|Boyd|1988|p=282}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|2<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3747|title=Carriage 2 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=28 June 2000|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|[[File:Talyllyn Carriage No 2.JPG|150px|Carriage No. 2]]\n|[[Brown, Marshalls and Co. Ltd.|Brown, Marshalls]]\n|1866\n|18\n|\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|3<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cs.rhrp.org.uk/se/CarriageInfo.asp?Ref=3748|title=Carriage 3 on Vintage Carriages Trust database|date=24 August 2003|accessdate=16 July 2008|publisher=Vintage Carriages Trust}}</ref>\n|align=\"